WEBVTT

00:07.090 --> 00:10.052
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:10.052 --> 00:15.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.140 --> 00:17.100
<i>- My name is Nick Zentella.</i>

00:17.100 --> 00:22.481
I am 39 years old.
And I am a geologist.

00:22.481 --> 00:24.525
<i>I would say that,</i>
<i>being a geologist,</i>

00:24.525 --> 00:25.484
<i>I do have a little</i>
<i>bit of extra insight</i>

00:25.484 --> 00:27.069
<i>in the materials.</i>

00:27.069 --> 00:28.237
Not that I have a very
technical approach

00:28.237 --> 00:29.988
to blacksmithing.

00:29.988 --> 00:33.283
I'm more a pound away
and see what happens.

00:33.283 --> 00:35.077
<i>- My name is Dwight.</i>
<i>I'm 52 years old.</i>

00:35.077 --> 00:37.079
I'm from Harford County,
Maryland.

00:37.079 --> 00:39.748
My confidence level for winning
the competition,

00:39.748 --> 00:43.085
barring the heat,
80% or 90%.

00:43.085 --> 00:44.920
'Cause I'm that good.

00:44.920 --> 00:47.089
- My name is Brian Neville.
I'm 31.

00:47.089 --> 00:50.759
I would describe myself as
slightly anal, overly punctual,

00:50.759 --> 00:52.386
very coarse.

00:52.386 --> 00:58.475
If you're late, I can be very,
uh...mean.

00:58.475 --> 01:01.687
<i>- My name's Alex Eisenberg.</i>
<i>I'm 29 years old.</i>

01:01.687 --> 01:04.731
I own a tattoo shop and am
a full-time tattoo artist,

01:04.731 --> 01:06.733
as well as bladesmith.

01:06.733 --> 01:08.318
<i>Most of my tattoos are</i>
<i>a representation of something</i>

01:08.318 --> 01:10.445
<i>that's happened to me.</i>

01:10.445 --> 01:12.281
And the rest of them are just
stuff that I thought was cool,

01:12.281 --> 01:15.367
and I liked, and I said,
"I want that one."

01:15.367 --> 01:17.578
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:17.578 --> 01:19.538
You're here
for three timed rounds

01:19.538 --> 01:21.582
of edged weapon-making
competition

01:21.582 --> 01:23.250
designed to test
every aspect of your skills.

01:23.250 --> 01:25.294
At the end of each round,
you'll present your work

01:25.294 --> 01:28.255
to our panel of expert judges.

01:28.255 --> 01:31.675
ABS master smith J. Neilson.

01:31.675 --> 01:33.844
Next, historic weapons
re-creation specialist

01:33.844 --> 01:35.554
David Baker.

01:35.554 --> 01:37.723
And last, edged and impact
weapons specialist

01:37.723 --> 01:39.600
Doug Marcaida.

01:39.600 --> 01:42.144
These are the men that
ultimately decide which of you

01:42.144 --> 01:44.187
is our next
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:44.187 --> 01:46.356
and leaves here with that check
for ten grand.

01:46.356 --> 01:48.233
All right.

01:48.233 --> 01:51.236
It's one thing to be able
to make a signature blade

01:51.236 --> 01:53.196
in your signature style
and design that blade.

01:53.196 --> 01:55.198
It's a fantastic skill.

01:55.198 --> 01:57.326
An entirely different skill set

01:57.326 --> 02:00.829
is making a blade
of somebody else's design.

02:00.829 --> 02:03.332
So, today, there will be
no signature blades.

02:03.332 --> 02:06.043
You'll be making this.

02:06.043 --> 02:08.295
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:08.295 --> 02:11.673
Adopted by the United States
Marine Corps in 1942,

02:11.673 --> 02:13.550
the Ka-Bar fighting knife has
seen action during Korea,

02:13.550 --> 02:15.761
Vietnam,
Desert Shield/Desert Storm,

02:15.761 --> 02:18.889
and Iraqi Freedom conflicts.

02:18.889 --> 02:20.557
Keep in mind that,
in the second round,

02:20.557 --> 02:22.351
you'll be attaching
handles to those blades,

02:22.351 --> 02:24.728
turning them into fully
functioning fighting weapons

02:24.728 --> 02:27.189
that will be tested for
strength and durability

02:27.189 --> 02:30.984
in a paint can chop and stab,

02:30.984 --> 02:34.404
and edge retention
in a leather bag slice.

02:34.404 --> 02:36.531
Do I have any questions?

02:36.531 --> 02:37.783
- Where's my steel?

02:37.783 --> 02:39.576
- That's an excellent question.

02:39.576 --> 02:42.788
Today,
you'll be using this steel.

02:42.788 --> 02:45.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:45.540 --> 02:50.712
Gentlemen, these are
one-by-one cubes of W-1 steel.

02:50.712 --> 02:53.507
You'll have to forge weld these
together to have enough steel

02:53.507 --> 02:55.133
to make your blades.

02:55.133 --> 02:56.718
Keep an eye on that clock,
bladesmiths,

02:56.718 --> 02:58.178
because when
the time runs out

02:58.178 --> 02:59.888
and the judges inspect
your work,

02:59.888 --> 03:01.682
one of you will have to
surrender your blade

03:01.682 --> 03:02.974
and leave The Forge.

03:02.974 --> 03:04.893
Your three hours starts...

03:04.893 --> 03:06.436
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:06.436 --> 03:08.814
Now.

03:08.814 --> 03:11.858
Talk to me a little bit about
the Ka-Bar fighting knife.

03:11.858 --> 03:14.027
- It's one of the most iconic
military blades

03:14.027 --> 03:16.113
we can say that
is American-made.

03:16.113 --> 03:20.033
The design alone is very useful
as a fighting utility blade.

03:20.033 --> 03:22.077
Before the Ka-Bar
fighting knives came up,

03:22.077 --> 03:24.371
the military had, like,
a stiletto-type blade.

03:24.371 --> 03:25.789
But they found that
it was only workable

03:25.789 --> 03:27.582
as a killing blade,

03:27.582 --> 03:30.669
so they wanted to make
a fighting utility knife.

03:30.669 --> 03:33.213
- You only want to carry
so much stuff around with you.

03:33.213 --> 03:34.923
If you get multi-purpose out
of your tools,

03:34.923 --> 03:36.341
it's a great thing.

03:36.341 --> 03:37.759
- So the Ka-Bar was made

03:37.759 --> 03:39.469
to have a certain amount
of flex in it,

03:39.469 --> 03:41.596
so you can actually use it
to pry a crate lid off

03:41.596 --> 03:44.224
or use it to open cans
and things like that,

03:44.224 --> 03:45.559
and still be able
to re-sharpen it

03:45.559 --> 03:47.686
and put an edge back
on that.

03:47.686 --> 03:49.646
<i>- I think the most difficult</i>
<i>part about creating a Ka-Bar</i>

03:49.646 --> 03:51.648
<i>is that it's such</i>
<i>a recognizable knife.</i>

03:51.648 --> 03:53.483
When you tattoo
Mickey Mouse on someone,

03:53.483 --> 03:55.360
it's got to look
like Mickey Mouse.

03:55.360 --> 03:57.237
<i>My plan of attack</i>
<i>for the cubes is that</i>

03:57.237 --> 03:59.865
<i>I'm going to make</i>
<i>four different stacks</i>

03:59.865 --> 04:01.658
so four stacks of three,
where I can then

04:01.658 --> 04:03.577
<i>weld the four stacks together,</i>

04:03.577 --> 04:06.037
<i>and then draw that out</i>
<i>to my final billet.</i>

04:06.037 --> 04:07.914
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:07.914 --> 04:11.334
- My plan of attack is
to weld four cubes together.

04:11.334 --> 04:12.878
- Dwight's cubes are looking
pretty good right now.

04:12.878 --> 04:13.962
- Yeah, it looks like he's
getting his weld set

04:13.962 --> 04:15.380
pretty nicely.

04:15.380 --> 04:17.382
- How would you go about it,
Jay?

04:17.382 --> 04:21.178
- I'd take a three or four
stack, tack weld them together,

04:21.178 --> 04:23.597
get 'em nice and hot,
and just put 'em upright.

04:23.597 --> 04:25.098
Squeeze 'em down on the press,

04:25.098 --> 04:26.391
and that way
you can forge weld them

04:26.391 --> 04:28.560
into little longer lengths.

04:28.560 --> 04:30.937
<i>- I'm really apprehensive</i>
<i>about working with the W-1,</i>

04:30.937 --> 04:33.148
<i>because I've never used it.</i>

04:33.148 --> 04:34.858
<i>As for making this blade,</i>
<i>it's going to be hard for me,</i>

04:34.858 --> 04:36.777
because I like to
take my time to

04:36.777 --> 04:39.613
<i>make sure everything</i>
<i>is the best I can get it.</i>

04:39.613 --> 04:42.491
So, we have to really put
the accelerator down on it.

04:42.491 --> 04:43.700
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:43.700 --> 04:45.452
<i>- I am incredibly relieved</i>

04:45.452 --> 04:47.120
<i>that it's just one steel</i>
<i>that we're working with.</i>

04:47.120 --> 04:49.748
Unfortunately, that steel
is in multiple pieces.

04:49.748 --> 04:52.793
<i>I'm going to stack</i>
<i>my 12 cubes,</i>

04:52.793 --> 04:55.545
<i>because at the end of it</i>
<i>I'll be as close to a billet</i>

04:55.545 --> 04:57.672
to where all I have to do
is drill it out.

04:57.672 --> 04:59.591
- That's a heck of a stack that
Brian's got together there.

04:59.591 --> 05:00.842
- [laughs]
- Holy cow.

05:00.842 --> 05:02.594
- That is a huge stack
of steel.

05:02.594 --> 05:05.472
- We've seen before
what happens when we have

05:05.472 --> 05:07.766
thin lengths of steel,
and they make too high a stack

05:07.766 --> 05:09.559
and starts folding over.

05:09.559 --> 05:12.020
Brian's got to be really gentle
on that press.

05:12.020 --> 05:13.897
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:13.897 --> 05:15.232
<i>- To create</i>
<i>a successful knife,</i>

05:15.232 --> 05:16.817
I'm going to have to
figure out a way

05:16.817 --> 05:19.361
to hold those little
metal cubes together,

05:19.361 --> 05:21.822
<i>and get 'em forge welded.</i>

05:21.822 --> 05:23.615
- I'm going to be honest,
when I revealed the cubes,

05:23.615 --> 05:25.325
Nick looked like
he [bleep] his pants.

05:25.325 --> 05:27.285
<i>- I have not had</i>
<i>a lot of experience</i>

05:27.285 --> 05:30.247
<i>with large masses</i>
<i>of loose cubes.</i>

05:30.247 --> 05:32.165
I'm going to see what happens.

05:32.165 --> 05:34.125
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:34.125 --> 05:35.919
<i>- I get them stacked,</i>
<i>get everything up</i>

05:35.919 --> 05:37.921
to welding temperature,
and then I run over

05:37.921 --> 05:39.589
<i>to the hydraulic press.</i>

05:39.589 --> 05:40.715
<i>I feel confident</i>
<i>I'll be able to get</i>

05:40.715 --> 05:42.634
<i>all my forge welds to stick.</i>

05:42.634 --> 05:45.804
- With Brian having all those
blocks stacked together,

05:45.804 --> 05:48.014
it'd be very easy if he pushed
a little too hard on that press

05:48.014 --> 05:49.140
to blow things off.

05:49.140 --> 05:50.767
But he went slow and steady,

05:50.767 --> 05:52.686
and did a nice job
of putting them together.

05:52.686 --> 05:56.064
- J. Neilson, he has that eye
that critiques everything.

05:56.064 --> 05:57.899
<i>He's a master smith.</i>
<i>I respect him.</i>

05:57.899 --> 05:59.818
<i>But he scares me to death.</i>

05:59.818 --> 06:01.486
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:01.486 --> 06:02.404
<i>- So far,</i>
<i>I'm getting clean welds.</i>

06:02.404 --> 06:04.322
<i>Everything is sticking.</i>

06:04.322 --> 06:06.658
- Well, Alex, he took
a single stack--four of them,

06:06.658 --> 06:09.411
flattened them down
basically into buttons,

06:09.411 --> 06:10.787
and that should give him enough
steel to make his blade,

06:10.787 --> 06:12.497
I think.
- Oh, yeah.

06:12.497 --> 06:14.875
<i>- So, my wife smells</i>
<i>everything she sees.</i>

06:14.875 --> 06:16.293
<i>Anything she picks up</i>
<i>in a store,</i>

06:16.293 --> 06:17.586
she smells it
for some reason.

06:17.586 --> 06:19.129
And I guess that
carried over for me.

06:19.129 --> 06:20.839
<i>I put my metal in the fire,</i>

06:20.839 --> 06:22.757
<i>and then I immediately</i>
<i>smelled my flux.</i>

06:22.757 --> 06:25.468
- Alex is smelling his flux
to make sure it's good.

06:25.468 --> 06:28.096
- Is he like,
"Is this happening?"

06:28.096 --> 06:29.222
Stop doing that.

06:29.222 --> 06:31.016
- You got a stock in flux?

06:31.016 --> 06:32.976
- [laughs]
No, I make my own,

06:32.976 --> 06:34.895
so I don't worry about it.

06:34.895 --> 06:38.273
I was just too curious about
what it smelled like.

06:38.273 --> 06:40.150
It didn't smell like anything.

06:40.150 --> 06:41.318
- Are you all right there,
Dwight?

06:41.318 --> 06:42.944
- Yes, sir.
- Cool.

06:42.944 --> 06:44.487
- So far, I ain't fell out yet,
buddy.

06:44.487 --> 06:45.989
- [laughs]

06:45.989 --> 06:48.199
- I'm feeling good
with the forge

06:48.199 --> 06:50.660
<i>and the way</i>
<i>the billet is coming out.</i>

06:50.660 --> 06:52.454
I've been working with metal
my whole life,

06:52.454 --> 06:55.457
so welding is not
an issue for me.

06:55.457 --> 06:57.417
This is my first Ka-Bar,

06:57.417 --> 06:59.919
but I've made plenty of
nice knives that resemble.

06:59.919 --> 07:03.214
I get all this confidence from
being an industrial mechanic.

07:03.214 --> 07:05.675
<i>My goal is to retire,</i>

07:05.675 --> 07:08.094
and spend the rest of
that time making knives.

07:08.094 --> 07:09.763
The forge welds
look good so far.

07:09.763 --> 07:12.682
So, I'm praying for the best.

07:12.682 --> 07:14.309
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:14.309 --> 07:16.811
<i>- I have never made</i>
<i>a Ka-Bar before.</i>

07:16.811 --> 07:19.272
It's a more modern style
that I don't usually do.

07:19.272 --> 07:21.900
<i>There's a lot of lines that</i>
<i>have to line up perfectly,</i>

07:21.900 --> 07:23.818
<i>and if any angle</i>
<i>is slightly off,</i>

07:23.818 --> 07:25.654
<i>everybody's going to see it.</i>

07:25.654 --> 07:26.821
- Even though
this is a shorter blade

07:26.821 --> 07:28.198
than we do
a lot of times,

07:28.198 --> 07:30.450
it isn't
a signature-style blade.

07:30.450 --> 07:33.703
It's a blade shape
that we want them to make.

07:33.703 --> 07:36.998
- And just like the military,
pay attention to the details.

07:36.998 --> 07:39.918
- I am taking my time because
I want to get everything right.

07:39.918 --> 07:41.753
This is definitely
out of my wheelhouse.

07:41.753 --> 07:44.130
I've never tried to do a weld
like this before.

07:44.130 --> 07:45.715
- Nick is back over to press.

07:45.715 --> 07:48.301
He's got his short stack
of steel there.

07:48.301 --> 07:49.678
Round stack of steel.

07:49.678 --> 07:51.096
- Looks like
it's sticking together.

07:51.096 --> 07:52.889
- Yeah,
his burger is welding up.

07:52.889 --> 07:56.101
- It went from a Big Mac
to a double cheeseburger.

07:56.101 --> 07:57.769
- I am definitely concerned

07:57.769 --> 07:59.729
that I'm going
a little bit slow,

07:59.729 --> 08:03.233
<i>but I'm just hoping</i>
<i>to catch up in the next steps.</i>

08:03.233 --> 08:04.317
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:04.317 --> 08:06.152
- Bladesmiths,

08:06.152 --> 08:09.280
you have just two hours
to finish your Ka-Bars.

08:09.280 --> 08:11.116
<i>- After drawing it out</i>
<i>a few times,</i>

08:11.116 --> 08:13.243
<i>I have decided</i>
<i>it's forged welded enough</i>

08:13.243 --> 08:15.286
to where
I think it's stable.

08:15.286 --> 08:17.831
<i>My perimeter welds on</i>

08:17.831 --> 08:19.916
almost all my cubes
going up the sides split.

08:19.916 --> 08:22.794
[bleep, bleep, bleep].

08:22.794 --> 08:25.088
- Uh-oh, uh-oh.
- Ooh, watch out.

08:25.088 --> 08:26.923
<i>- Instantly</i>
<i>the sweat comes on.</i>

08:26.923 --> 08:28.758
All the pressure
in the world is there.

08:28.758 --> 08:30.927
Luckily,
I can think on my feet,

08:30.927 --> 08:34.097
and I start forging
around my delams.

08:34.097 --> 08:36.766
- He'd probably be better off
to start drawing that out

08:36.766 --> 08:38.476
and grind the edge off.
- Yeah.

08:38.476 --> 08:40.145
<i>- I've persevered</i>
<i>through bladesmithing</i>

08:40.145 --> 08:42.397
<i>out of sheer</i>
<i>fool-headedness.</i>

08:42.397 --> 08:43.606
You tell me I can't walk
through that door,

08:43.606 --> 08:46.317
<i>I'll walk through that door.</i>

08:46.317 --> 08:49.696
- I just wish
there was music playing.

08:49.696 --> 08:52.032
Now that the end of
my billet is nice and clean,

08:52.032 --> 08:53.742
<i>I'm going to start</i>
<i>forging in my tip.</i>

08:53.742 --> 08:57.245
- Alex, look at him
aggressively hammering away

08:57.245 --> 08:58.621
on his billet.

08:58.621 --> 08:59.748
- Just the kind of
hammer strokes

08:59.748 --> 09:01.666
I like seeing a smith use.

09:01.666 --> 09:03.668
- I haven't had
any professional training.

09:03.668 --> 09:05.879
<i>All the learning I've done</i>
<i>has been trial and error.</i>

09:05.879 --> 09:07.672
<i>We like to say that,</i>
<i>to make a good knife,</i>

09:07.672 --> 09:09.507
you first have to
fill five gallon buckets

09:09.507 --> 09:11.176
with not good knives.

09:11.176 --> 09:12.969
All right.
Now we're forging the knife.

09:12.969 --> 09:14.763
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:14.763 --> 09:16.973
- Hope the heat's not getting
to Dwight.

09:16.973 --> 09:19.309
I haven't seen him pull
anything out of that forge

09:19.309 --> 09:20.477
in a few minutes.

09:20.477 --> 09:22.228
- I'm worried about him.

09:22.228 --> 09:24.522
- I'm not feeling good.
I'm just very hot.

09:24.522 --> 09:26.232
<i>I'm going to keep driving</i>
<i>and pushing myself.</i>

09:26.232 --> 09:28.109
I want to finish this knife.

09:28.109 --> 09:31.112
- One of the things that
you cannot experience

09:31.112 --> 09:33.907
by watching this show
is the heat.

09:33.907 --> 09:38.161
You have to be as physically
prepared as you are mentally,

09:38.161 --> 09:42.540
because it will drain a smith
to the point of breaking.

09:42.540 --> 09:45.668
- I'm starting to get shaking
in my hands and my arms,

09:45.668 --> 09:48.379
<i>and I don't want to quit.</i>
<i>I'm not a quitter.</i>

09:48.379 --> 09:51.216
- This is a serious
medical concern right now.

09:54.636 --> 09:57.013
<i>- I want to finish this knife.</i>

09:57.013 --> 09:59.849
Unless I'm forced to stop,
I'm not giving up.

09:59.849 --> 10:00.767
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:02.227 --> 10:03.186
- [bleep].

10:05.480 --> 10:09.109
- One of our bladesmiths has
been pulled from competition

10:09.109 --> 10:10.527
for medical reasons.

10:10.527 --> 10:12.195
- It's not worth
the physical risk.

10:12.195 --> 10:13.279
- No.

10:13.279 --> 10:14.531
<i>- I knew she was right,</i>

10:14.531 --> 10:15.990
but I didn't want
to believe it.

10:15.990 --> 10:18.284
<i>I am very upset.</i>

10:18.284 --> 10:20.537
I tried my best.
I just couldn't handle it.

10:20.537 --> 10:24.499
- It would be a mistake for
any of these smiths to assume

10:24.499 --> 10:26.584
that they're automatically into
the next round

10:26.584 --> 10:29.754
just because one of the guys
medically dropped.

10:29.754 --> 10:31.214
- You can always boot
somebody out.

10:31.214 --> 10:32.757
- No one is safe.

10:32.757 --> 10:34.759
If anyone hands in
an incomplete blade,

10:34.759 --> 10:35.969
they could be going home.

10:35.969 --> 10:38.221
[hammering]

10:38.221 --> 10:39.639
- Oops.

10:39.639 --> 10:42.725
I am very clumsy in the shop.

10:42.725 --> 10:44.477
[sighs]

10:44.477 --> 10:46.771
I drop things all the time.

10:46.771 --> 10:48.314
That's just my usual M. O.

10:48.314 --> 10:51.192
[loud scratching]

10:51.192 --> 10:53.194
- In both India and Nepal

10:53.194 --> 10:55.113
you see the smiths sitting on
the ground while they work.

10:55.113 --> 10:57.115
- I don't think
Nick is from Nepal.

10:57.115 --> 10:59.325
<i>- I do like to work</i>
<i>on the ground.</i>

10:59.325 --> 11:01.911
<i>It's a very traditional way</i>
<i>of smithing.</i>

11:01.911 --> 11:05.874
And I'm reasonably flexible,
so I just make the most of it.

11:05.874 --> 11:07.750
- What Nick has doesn't look
anything like a Ka-Bar.

11:07.750 --> 11:08.918
- Yeah.

11:08.918 --> 11:10.295
<i>- It's looking pretty oval,</i>

11:10.295 --> 11:12.505
which is probably
less than ideal.

11:12.505 --> 11:15.800
<i>I'm just going to keep going</i>
<i>until the time runs out.</i>

11:15.800 --> 11:19.470
- 30 minutes, bladesmiths!

11:19.470 --> 11:21.556
- I'm worried more about
the delam towards the edge.

11:21.556 --> 11:24.058
I'm hoping to grind them out.

11:24.058 --> 11:26.186
<i>If it wasn't for those delams,</i>

11:26.186 --> 11:28.354
I would be the happiest kid
in the schoolyard right now.

11:28.354 --> 11:30.231
Delams suck.

11:30.231 --> 11:31.357
The delam's not coming out.

11:31.357 --> 11:32.692
<i>I'm out of time.</i>

11:32.692 --> 11:34.611
I have
to heat-treat this blade.

11:34.611 --> 11:36.654
Hey, Alex,
you got a magnet there?

11:36.654 --> 11:39.240
You're the man, brother.
Thank you.

11:39.240 --> 11:41.367
- Brian and Alex are kind of
working together a little bit.

11:41.367 --> 11:43.369
- Whoo!

11:43.369 --> 11:45.622
- Brian needed a magnet.
Alex handed it to him.

11:45.622 --> 11:47.540
- Too much of a bromance
going on.

11:47.540 --> 11:49.459
<i>- Alex saving me on this one.</i>

11:49.459 --> 11:51.336
It's almost like we've been
working together for years,

11:51.336 --> 11:53.171
and I've never met the man
before in my life.

11:53.171 --> 11:55.882
- Well, some people do
find love in "Forged in Fire."

11:55.882 --> 11:57.050
[laughter]

11:57.050 --> 11:58.551
<i>[playful music]</i>

11:58.551 --> 11:59.969
[laughter]

11:59.969 --> 12:01.137
- Oh, they did it.
They did it.

12:01.137 --> 12:04.682
- I'm in a bromance.
Oh, man.

12:04.682 --> 12:07.769
Whoo!
I like that.

12:07.769 --> 12:09.395
So, I've left myself
with enough time

12:09.395 --> 12:11.564
to thermocycle
the blade twice

12:11.564 --> 12:14.317
before putting it in for
its final ramp for its quench.

12:14.317 --> 12:16.402
<i>[rock music]</i>

12:16.402 --> 12:18.529
- All right,
so we got two blades quenched.

12:18.529 --> 12:20.740
[scraping]

12:20.740 --> 12:23.159
- I'll take it.

12:23.159 --> 12:24.994
<i>- There's not a whole</i>
<i>lot of time left,</i>

12:24.994 --> 12:27.080
so I got my work
cut out for me.

12:27.080 --> 12:30.917
- All right, Nick, you got 13
minutes to quench a blade here.

12:30.917 --> 12:32.835
<i>- I'm a little bit nervous</i>
<i>about the quench</i>

12:32.835 --> 12:34.420
because I don't have
a whole lot of time

12:34.420 --> 12:35.964
to reheat if I have to.

12:35.964 --> 12:37.632
What the hell?

12:37.632 --> 12:40.718
- And...Nick just quenched.
- There we go.

12:40.718 --> 12:43.096
[scraping]

12:43.096 --> 12:45.139
- Seems pretty hard.

12:45.139 --> 12:50.436
- Ten, nine, eight, seven, six,

12:50.436 --> 12:55.692
five, four, three, two, one.

12:55.692 --> 12:57.694
Shut down your machines.
Drop your tools.

12:57.694 --> 13:00.029
First round
of competition is over.

13:00.029 --> 13:01.281
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

13:01.281 --> 13:03.408
<i>- I'm still nervous.</i>

13:03.408 --> 13:06.786
I know that there are a couple
of spots for those laminations

13:06.786 --> 13:08.997
that look like
they're less than perfect.

13:08.997 --> 13:11.708
If it's not what it's supposed
to be, I'm not going on,

13:11.708 --> 13:13.376
whether Dwight's there or not.

13:13.376 --> 13:14.460
♪ ♪

13:14.460 --> 13:15.878
- All right, bladesmiths,

13:15.878 --> 13:17.588
in this first round
of competition,

13:17.588 --> 13:19.716
we threw out the old
signature blade parameter,

13:19.716 --> 13:21.718
and we wanted Ka-Bar
fighting knives.

13:21.718 --> 13:24.470
We also gave you plenty
of W-1 steel cubes

13:24.470 --> 13:26.472
to forge weld together
to make that happen.

13:26.472 --> 13:28.516
Now it's time to see
how you did.

13:28.516 --> 13:30.685
Although Dwight did not
complete a blade,

13:30.685 --> 13:32.895
one of you
still could be going home

13:32.895 --> 13:35.189
if you fail
to meet parameters.

13:35.189 --> 13:36.566
Nick.
You're up first.

13:36.566 --> 13:39.277
Please present your work
to the judges.

13:39.277 --> 13:41.070
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:41.070 --> 13:42.947
<i>- The first thing I see</i>
<i>is the profile.</i>

13:42.947 --> 13:44.615
<i>It kind of has</i>
<i>that football shape.</i>

13:44.615 --> 13:46.826
You had a steel football out
there for a while.

13:46.826 --> 13:48.411
You managed to push that down,
which is great.

13:48.411 --> 13:50.163
<i>There are seams here.</i>

13:50.163 --> 13:51.456
<i>Hopefully you'll be able to</i>
<i>grind them out.</i>

13:51.456 --> 13:53.583
None of them look like cracks.

13:53.583 --> 13:55.752
I'd love to see you get these
lines parallel to one another,

13:55.752 --> 13:57.920
and then really develop
that clip,

13:57.920 --> 13:59.881
really develop
the point on that blade,

13:59.881 --> 14:02.800
to get this to be a Ka-Bar.

14:02.800 --> 14:06.095
- Now, your blade.
At least we can see a formation

14:06.095 --> 14:07.847
of what could be a Ka-bar.

14:07.847 --> 14:09.599
There are some issues here
that you have to fix.

14:09.599 --> 14:11.350
We know you got the skill
to do that.

14:11.350 --> 14:12.518
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:12.518 --> 14:13.936
- Brian, you're up.

14:13.936 --> 14:15.772
Please present your work
to the judges.

14:15.772 --> 14:19.067
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:19.067 --> 14:20.651
- All right, Brian.
I really liked the technique

14:20.651 --> 14:22.153
you used for forging
these together.

14:22.153 --> 14:24.072
It was a risky technique,

14:24.072 --> 14:25.865
but you actually pulled it
together nicely,

14:25.865 --> 14:28.326
aside from the fact
that your tang is so low.

14:28.326 --> 14:29.327
It's not centered.

14:29.327 --> 14:31.037
- I have a few ideas.

14:31.037 --> 14:33.498
- Make sure they're ideas
that are gonna work.

14:33.498 --> 14:35.917
Right here
you've got a major issue.

14:35.917 --> 14:39.545
This is the weak point
of the whole knife right here.

14:39.545 --> 14:42.256
And you've got a very
wide open seam right here,

14:42.256 --> 14:44.133
and another one right here.

14:44.133 --> 14:46.385
So, I'd be concerned if I went
and smacked this blade

14:46.385 --> 14:49.889
on the table right now,
it'd snap it right now.

14:49.889 --> 14:52.225
- All right, Brian.
Right off the bat,

14:52.225 --> 14:54.560
that looks like
the shape we asked for.

14:54.560 --> 14:56.771
Good job in getting the profile
of a Ka-Bar knife.

14:56.771 --> 14:58.689
Moving forward, though,

14:58.689 --> 15:02.026
I'd like to see this not just
look like a Ka-Bar,

15:02.026 --> 15:05.279
but perform very much
like a Ka-Bar should.

15:05.279 --> 15:06.656
- All right, Alex.
You're up.

15:06.656 --> 15:08.699
Please present your work
to the judges.

15:08.699 --> 15:11.577
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:11.577 --> 15:13.496
- All right, Alex.
You got a nice profile here.

15:13.496 --> 15:15.456
And you got a lot of blade.

15:15.456 --> 15:19.168
Your blade is kind of going
like a snake in the water.

15:19.168 --> 15:21.462
Not too bad.
You got enough to clean it up.

15:21.462 --> 15:24.757
I'd like to see this evened up
a little bit more.

15:24.757 --> 15:28.594
This almost looks more like
a bowie fighter than a Ka-Bar.

15:28.594 --> 15:31.347
- Okay, I like the shape,
but again,

15:31.347 --> 15:33.307
it's a bowie shape,
as opposed to a Ka-Bar shape.

15:33.307 --> 15:37.145
The biggest issues
that I see are one,

15:37.145 --> 15:39.564
two's right about here,
and three.

15:39.564 --> 15:41.232
There are three cracks.
They're there.

15:41.232 --> 15:43.359
And they're deep.

15:43.359 --> 15:46.445
You really have
to deal with those.

15:46.445 --> 15:49.323
- After examining your weapons
with the parameters in mind,

15:49.323 --> 15:51.951
the judges have decided,

15:51.951 --> 15:55.079
you are all moving on
to the next round.

15:55.079 --> 15:56.205
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

15:56.205 --> 15:57.957
it's time to turn them

15:57.957 --> 16:00.001
into fully-functional
Ka-Bar fighting knives,

16:00.001 --> 16:01.627
by attaching handles to them.

16:01.627 --> 16:04.881
Because we had you make
specifically Ka-Bars,

16:04.881 --> 16:07.842
we also want specifically
Ka-Bar handles.

16:07.842 --> 16:10.428
You're gonna do
stacked leather handles

16:10.428 --> 16:13.014
with a guard
and a hammer pommel.

16:13.014 --> 16:17.310
You will notice that there is
a classic Ka-Bar build shelf

16:17.310 --> 16:19.896
that's at your disposal.

16:19.896 --> 16:21.439
You'll have three hours
to complete this.

16:21.439 --> 16:23.441
Now, if some of your blades

16:23.441 --> 16:25.026
do not have the profile
of the Ka-Bar,

16:25.026 --> 16:26.861
you'll have to fix this.

16:26.861 --> 16:28.738
Use your time wisely,

16:28.738 --> 16:30.531
because when the time runs out,

16:30.531 --> 16:32.950
your blades will be tested for
strength and durability,

16:32.950 --> 16:35.786
stabbing and slashing
into a paint can.

16:35.786 --> 16:40.374
And for edge retention,
cutting into a leather bag.

16:40.374 --> 16:43.377
I'll remind you that after
your weapons have been tested,

16:43.377 --> 16:45.171
one of you will have to
surrender your blade

16:45.171 --> 16:46.589
and leave The Forge.

16:46.589 --> 16:49.634
Good luck.
Your time starts now.

16:49.634 --> 16:52.762
- Stacked leather handle.
How complicated is that?

16:52.762 --> 16:55.306
- You got to cut each
individual disc,

16:55.306 --> 16:57.225
and you got to
cut the slot in each one.

16:57.225 --> 16:58.976
It's just time-consuming.

16:58.976 --> 17:00.561
This is "Forged in Fire."
It's not gonna be easy.

17:00.561 --> 17:01.854
- These guys are
going to hate us.

17:01.854 --> 17:03.272
- That's all right.

17:03.272 --> 17:05.441
<i>- I'm absolutely</i>
<i>one step closer</i>

17:05.441 --> 17:06.817
to winning
"Forged in Fire,"

17:06.817 --> 17:08.236
<i>but I've got to</i>
<i>address the delam</i>

17:08.236 --> 17:10.446
<i>in the center of my blade.</i>

17:10.446 --> 17:12.448
<i>In order to fix that, I think</i>
<i>if I just keep up the spine,</i>

17:12.448 --> 17:14.033
it'll hold just fine.

17:14.033 --> 17:15.493
- Brian cut a piece of that
angle iron

17:15.493 --> 17:17.286
that he had out there,

17:17.286 --> 17:18.454
and he's going to weld that
onto the top of it.

17:18.454 --> 17:20.081
- Brian's got me worried,

17:20.081 --> 17:21.165
'cause he'll just
cover the surface,

17:21.165 --> 17:22.708
have voids in the center,

17:22.708 --> 17:23.918
and that's just gonna be
the same flaw

17:23.918 --> 17:25.544
that he already had.

17:25.544 --> 17:27.421
- There's so much to do
in this round

17:27.421 --> 17:29.882
that I don't really have too
much time for the fun stuff,

17:29.882 --> 17:31.259
but the bromance
is still alive.

17:31.259 --> 17:34.845
<i>[playful music]</i>

17:34.845 --> 17:36.347
- You got a volume knob
on that thing?

17:36.347 --> 17:38.683
- Nope.

17:38.683 --> 17:41.102
- The most challenging thing to
get right in this round

17:41.102 --> 17:42.812
is going to be
addressing the cracks.

17:42.812 --> 17:44.981
- Let's talk about
what's going on with Alex.

17:44.981 --> 17:46.857
He's got cracks,

17:46.857 --> 17:48.276
but he's got plenty of stuff
to play with, right?

17:48.276 --> 17:49.944
- He's got a lot of material.

17:49.944 --> 17:52.154
The thing is, those cracks are
going to travel

17:52.154 --> 17:54.073
all the way
through that blade.

17:54.073 --> 17:56.409
- Unfortunately, I don't think
the cracks are fixable,

17:56.409 --> 17:58.494
<i>so what I'm going to do is</i>
<i>torch temper the spine</i>

17:58.494 --> 18:00.121
<i>in hopes to soften it up,</i>

18:00.121 --> 18:01.038
<i>so that the blade</i>
<i>will stay together</i>

18:01.038 --> 18:02.832
through all the testing.

18:02.832 --> 18:05.042
Dude, if I had music,
I'd be so happy right now.

18:05.042 --> 18:07.878
In my own shop, music helps me
keep track of time.

18:07.878 --> 18:10.256
<i>I play guitar,</i>
<i>and then I also play drums.</i>

18:10.256 --> 18:12.258
<i>I've played in everything from</i>
<i>blues bands to metal bands</i>

18:12.258 --> 18:13.676
<i>to jazz bands.</i>

18:13.676 --> 18:15.469
So, at this point,
one of the things

18:15.469 --> 18:16.721
that is making me
the most nervous

18:16.721 --> 18:18.973
is not having music playing.

18:21.350 --> 18:24.478
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

18:24.478 --> 18:26.272
- The first thing I'd do
is profile it

18:26.272 --> 18:27.481
so it looks like a Ka-Bar.

18:27.481 --> 18:29.025
- Nick has got enough metal

18:29.025 --> 18:30.651
to be able to make
those refinements.

18:30.651 --> 18:32.778
<i>- There's definitely</i>
<i>quite a ways to go</i>

18:32.778 --> 18:34.530
<i>before this really</i>
<i>looks like a Ka-Bar.</i>

18:34.530 --> 18:36.407
<i>The shape is</i>
<i>pretty complicated,</i>

18:36.407 --> 18:38.492
so it's making me kind of
nervous how much time

18:38.492 --> 18:39.577
I think this is
gonna take.

18:42.830 --> 18:44.790
<i>I would say that I am</i>
<i>definitely a trial-and-error</i>

18:44.790 --> 18:46.208
<i>kind of smith.</i>

18:46.208 --> 18:47.251
I try to read up a little bit

18:47.251 --> 18:48.836
before everything that I do,

18:48.836 --> 18:50.630
but I also just like
to wing it.

18:53.716 --> 18:56.260
- You have just two hours
remaining to finish your work!

18:56.260 --> 18:58.095
- So close.

18:58.095 --> 19:00.473
After I have my guard fitted
and welded in place,

19:00.473 --> 19:02.600
I can fix the tang.

19:02.600 --> 19:04.935
<i>The judges pointed out that</i>
<i>my tang was sitting too low.</i>

19:04.935 --> 19:06.812
- He's actually
intentionally bending it,

19:06.812 --> 19:08.939
because what he was trying to
do is pull it this way

19:08.939 --> 19:11.233
and pull it that way
to kind of bring it up.

19:11.233 --> 19:12.568
- Oh, okay.
- So at least his tang

19:12.568 --> 19:14.403
is centered on a pommel.
It's clever.

19:14.403 --> 19:15.905
- Getting better.

19:15.905 --> 19:18.449
After I get the offset
of my tang done,

19:18.449 --> 19:20.660
<i>I then proceed</i>
<i>to start building my handle.</i>

19:20.660 --> 19:21.911
I've never made a stacked
leather handle,

19:21.911 --> 19:23.663
so I'm worried about that.

19:23.663 --> 19:26.082
I don't want it to be flimsy
or squishy at all,

19:26.082 --> 19:29.001
<i>so carbon fiber is one of the</i>
<i>strongest things out there.</i>

19:29.001 --> 19:31.045
<i>And I cut up</i>
<i>four slabs of that</i>

19:31.045 --> 19:33.172
<i>to use as spacers</i>
<i>throughout my handle.</i>

19:33.172 --> 19:34.465
Fitted all.

19:34.465 --> 19:35.508
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:35.508 --> 19:36.509
- All right.

19:36.509 --> 19:38.511
So, at this point,

19:38.511 --> 19:40.471
my guard fits, my pommel fits,
my leather spacers fit.

19:40.471 --> 19:42.556
I'm going to start gluing
everything together.

19:42.556 --> 19:44.558
<i>I want to make sure</i>
<i>to get a nice layer of epoxy</i>

19:44.558 --> 19:47.269
<i>between every single</i>
<i>stack of leather.</i>

19:47.269 --> 19:49.397
So, I get the whole handle
put together,

19:49.397 --> 19:51.315
<i>and I grab the pin to</i>
<i>fit through my pommel,</i>

19:51.315 --> 19:52.817
<i>to keep it all in place.</i>

19:52.817 --> 19:54.694
Oh, come on, you mother[bleep].

19:54.694 --> 19:56.904
My pin's the wrong size,
and it's not gonna fit.

19:56.904 --> 19:59.115
- The pin wasn't prepped.

19:59.115 --> 20:00.408
- And the epoxy's curing up.

20:00.408 --> 20:01.909
- So, can Alex get this pin?

20:01.909 --> 20:04.120
That's the question.

20:04.120 --> 20:06.163
- I can't seem to find the pin
that's the size of the hole

20:06.163 --> 20:07.873
that I drilled in the pommel.

20:07.873 --> 20:10.376
This is not good.

20:10.376 --> 20:12.503
<i>I need to make sure</i>
<i>the pin can go through</i>

20:12.503 --> 20:14.046
<i>to secure the pommel</i>
<i>onto the knife.</i>

20:14.046 --> 20:15.131
[bleep] damn it.

20:15.131 --> 20:16.841
- The epoxy will be set

20:16.841 --> 20:18.968
in another minute and a half.

20:18.968 --> 20:21.762
<i>- If I can't get the pin,</i>
<i>my handle could break.</i>

20:24.974 --> 20:28.269
- Come on, you mother[bleep].

20:28.269 --> 20:29.895
My pin is the wrong size
and it's not going to fit.

20:29.895 --> 20:33.357
- The pin wasn't prepped.
- The epoxy's curing up.

20:33.357 --> 20:36.819
- So, can Alex get this pin?
That's the question.

20:36.819 --> 20:38.529
- I can't seem to find the pin
that's the size of the hole

20:38.529 --> 20:40.114
that I drilled in the pommel.

20:40.114 --> 20:41.741
<i>So, with time working</i>
<i>against me,</i>

20:41.741 --> 20:43.492
I start making my own pin

20:43.492 --> 20:44.994
<i>out of one</i>
<i>that I found in the pantry.</i>

20:44.994 --> 20:46.912
- All right, I think
Alex got it through.

20:46.912 --> 20:51.625
- [indistinct singing]

20:51.625 --> 20:53.669
- Blade's looking a lot
better than it was, though.

20:53.669 --> 20:55.629
- Yeah.

20:55.629 --> 20:58.132
- I feel like it is looking
pretty much like a Ka-Bar.

20:58.132 --> 21:00.259
<i>So, my plan for the guard</i>

21:00.259 --> 21:02.261
is to cut out a piece
of angle iron,

21:02.261 --> 21:04.263
<i>and then get it</i>
<i>to fit the blade.</i>

21:07.141 --> 21:08.476
<i>I'm trying to get</i>
<i>this guard to fit,</i>

21:08.476 --> 21:10.811
but it's just taking
too much time.

21:10.811 --> 21:16.484
<i>Usually I work</i>
<i>real, real slow.</i>

21:16.484 --> 21:19.069
And I cannot work
real, real slow here.

21:19.069 --> 21:22.364
I just have to get something
together in a big hurry.

21:22.364 --> 21:23.824
- He hasn't cut and drilled
any leather,

21:23.824 --> 21:25.785
punched any leather holes
or anything.

21:25.785 --> 21:27.578
He would be lucky if he can
even get that handle together

21:27.578 --> 21:29.705
before he runs out of time.

21:29.705 --> 21:33.000
- Two hours has lapped.

21:33.000 --> 21:35.252
<i>- After I get my stack made up</i>
<i>to the right dimension</i>

21:35.252 --> 21:37.338
that I believe I need,

21:37.338 --> 21:40.883
I put my pommel and washer on,
and I peen it all the way down.

21:40.883 --> 21:43.052
Of course.

21:43.052 --> 21:45.679
My leather still feels
a little too loose.

21:45.679 --> 21:48.390
- [laughs]
Oh, my God, man.

21:48.390 --> 21:50.267
Brian popped the cap
on a thing of super glue,

21:50.267 --> 21:52.686
and dumped it all over
that handle pin.

21:52.686 --> 21:54.230
- If he's going to
grind it anymore,

21:54.230 --> 21:55.314
it's just going to disappear.

21:55.314 --> 21:57.274
It's not going to penetrate.

21:57.274 --> 22:01.195
<i>- It's an instant cure</i>
<i>and my stack seems solid.</i>

22:01.195 --> 22:02.196
- 20 minutes!

22:02.196 --> 22:04.657
- Jesus [bleep].

22:04.657 --> 22:06.826
<i>The clock's definitely</i>
<i>getting to me a little bit</i>

22:06.826 --> 22:08.953
at this point.
I need to shape my handle

22:08.953 --> 22:10.955
and I need to sharpen my blade.

22:10.955 --> 22:13.666
<i>I'm a little bit concerned</i>
<i>about the chopping test.</i>

22:13.666 --> 22:15.334
<i>The cracks always</i>
<i>leave potential</i>

22:15.334 --> 22:17.253
<i>for there to be</i>
<i>a catastrophic failure.</i>

22:17.253 --> 22:19.046
<i>And I'll be damned</i>
<i>if I go home because of that.</i>

22:19.046 --> 22:20.714
Oh, I said a bad word.

22:20.714 --> 22:22.800
You'd think with
the tattoo shop and the band

22:22.800 --> 22:24.134
and the motorcycles
and the blacksmith

22:24.134 --> 22:26.095
that I'm a party animal.
But I am not.

22:26.095 --> 22:27.555
I am at home
with my wife and kid

22:27.555 --> 22:30.057
every opportunity I get.

22:30.057 --> 22:32.977
- I have less than 20 minutes,
and I don't even have a handle.

22:32.977 --> 22:35.604
I have just a big,
rectangular block of leather.

22:35.604 --> 22:37.940
- I haven't seen
any leather cut.

22:37.940 --> 22:41.443
I'm worried about Nick even
finishing this challenge.

22:41.443 --> 22:43.070
<i>- I'm a little out of control</i>

22:43.070 --> 22:45.656
trying to cut down
this leather on that handle.

22:45.656 --> 22:47.575
<i>I'm just hacking away</i>
<i>any way I can,</i>

22:47.575 --> 22:49.410
without getting blood
everywhere.

22:49.410 --> 22:51.412
- I get a feeling that
Nick has very few power tools

22:51.412 --> 22:53.455
in his shop.

22:53.455 --> 22:54.790
- Yeah, I mean, these grinders
will take that leather off

22:54.790 --> 22:55.958
in seconds.

22:55.958 --> 22:57.293
- If he was in Boy Scouts,

22:57.293 --> 22:58.711
they'd take away
his whittling badge.

22:58.711 --> 23:00.671
[laughter]

23:00.671 --> 23:05.634
- Ten, nine, eight, seven, six,

23:05.634 --> 23:11.015
five, four, three, two, one.

23:11.015 --> 23:12.141
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

23:12.141 --> 23:13.726
Drop your tools.

23:13.726 --> 23:17.104
This second round
of competition is over.

23:17.104 --> 23:19.857
- I feel relieved that
I made it through.

23:19.857 --> 23:21.108
<i>I think if I didn't</i>
<i>have cracks in this blade</i>

23:21.108 --> 23:22.735
<i>going into the final testing,</i>

23:22.735 --> 23:23.986
<i>I'd be sitting</i>
<i>a little bit taller,</i>

23:23.986 --> 23:25.905
and I'd feel
a little bit better.

23:25.905 --> 23:29.742
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to our strength test.

23:29.742 --> 23:31.785
Now, what I'm going to do is
take each of your knives.

23:31.785 --> 23:33.662
I'm going to thrust and chop
into these paint cans

23:33.662 --> 23:35.497
several times.

23:35.497 --> 23:37.750
I don't really care what
your blades do to the cans.

23:37.750 --> 23:39.960
It's more about what
the cans do to your blades.

23:39.960 --> 23:41.420
Nick, you're up first.
Are you ready?

23:41.420 --> 23:42.838
- As ready as I'm gonna get.

23:42.838 --> 23:44.840
- That's all I ask for.

23:44.840 --> 23:47.927
<i>- My biggest concern</i>
<i>is that the blade</i>

23:47.927 --> 23:49.511
<i>may not be sharp enough.</i>

23:49.511 --> 23:51.430
<i>It came out pretty thick,</i>

23:51.430 --> 23:53.766
and I didn't get to spend
enough time refining the edges

23:53.766 --> 23:55.601
<i>I would like.</i>

23:55.601 --> 23:58.520
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:58.520 --> 24:05.486
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:07.863 --> 24:09.740
- [grunting]

24:09.740 --> 24:11.241
- Phew.

24:11.241 --> 24:13.786
- I'm so glad I wore
my brown pants.

24:13.786 --> 24:16.413
- First off, your blade now
looks like a Ka-Bar,

24:16.413 --> 24:18.332
which is what we asked for.

24:18.332 --> 24:20.709
Not the most comfortable handle
I've ever held onto.

24:20.709 --> 24:23.003
There's really not much
in the way of indexing.

24:23.003 --> 24:24.922
I really needed
a glove for this.

24:24.922 --> 24:27.049
That being said,
you did make a good guard,

24:27.049 --> 24:28.634
and you did give me
a button on the back,

24:28.634 --> 24:30.469
so when I pull
from the stab,

24:30.469 --> 24:31.929
I've got something
to hold onto.

24:31.929 --> 24:33.806
It doesn't just
slide out of my hand.

24:33.806 --> 24:35.057
But the big issue is,

24:35.057 --> 24:36.976
a bunch of little chips in it.

24:36.976 --> 24:38.519
See, right there.

24:38.519 --> 24:40.354
There's a flake
still sticking out.

24:40.354 --> 24:41.772
You still have most of an edge,

24:41.772 --> 24:43.357
but now
it's partially serrated.

24:43.357 --> 24:45.150
But overall, it held up.
Good job.

24:45.150 --> 24:46.860
- Thank you.

24:46.860 --> 24:48.696
- Ready, Brian?

24:48.696 --> 24:49.738
- Go for it.

24:49.738 --> 24:52.408
- I'm going to.

24:52.408 --> 24:54.243
<i>- My gut is in a knot.</i>

24:54.243 --> 24:56.412
<i>I'm afraid of</i>
<i>my blade failing.</i>

24:56.412 --> 25:03.293
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:11.510 --> 25:15.973
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:15.973 --> 25:17.975
- [sighs]

25:17.975 --> 25:20.853
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:20.853 --> 25:23.272
- All right, Brian.
We obviously have an issue.

25:23.272 --> 25:24.982
The welding on that back bar,

25:24.982 --> 25:26.942
trying to re-enforce it
was a good idea.

25:26.942 --> 25:29.403
I think a little heat added
a little more stress to it.

25:29.403 --> 25:31.071
- [snickers]

25:31.071 --> 25:32.448
<i>It was somewhat expected,</i>

25:32.448 --> 25:34.700
but I am defeated
on the inside.

25:34.700 --> 25:37.119
- Bladesmiths, these weapons
tests are designed

25:37.119 --> 25:38.704
to be intentionally difficult

25:38.704 --> 25:40.581
to set you apart
from one another.

25:40.581 --> 25:43.167
Brian, your blade suffered
a catastrophic failure,

25:43.167 --> 25:45.169
but that doesn't mean that
you're out of this competition.

25:45.169 --> 25:48.338
One of our bladesmiths still
has to perform this test.

25:48.338 --> 25:50.132
So your fate and his fate

25:50.132 --> 25:53.177
ride entirely on the strength
of Alex's blade.

25:53.177 --> 25:54.762
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:54.762 --> 25:56.346
<i>- I'm pretty concerned.</i>

25:56.346 --> 25:57.890
<i>I've got a couple</i>
<i>of big cracks.</i>

25:57.890 --> 25:59.892
<i>I did my best,</i>
<i>but it's anyone's game.</i>

25:59.892 --> 26:01.810
We'll have to see
what happens.

26:23.165 --> 26:24.500
- Alex, nice job.

26:24.500 --> 26:25.751
Your edge held up very well.

26:25.751 --> 26:27.544
There's minor chipping,

26:27.544 --> 26:29.463
but overall you got most of
your edge on there.

26:29.463 --> 26:30.714
Good job.

26:30.714 --> 26:32.132
- Thank you.

26:32.132 --> 26:34.593
- Alex, your blade held up.

26:34.593 --> 26:36.929
Brian, that means that your
blade did not make the cut.

26:36.929 --> 26:39.014
You suffered
a catastrophic weapons failure

26:39.014 --> 26:39.932
in our strength test,

26:39.932 --> 26:41.600
and for that reason,

26:41.600 --> 26:44.019
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

26:44.019 --> 26:46.647
- Good job.
Good job.

26:46.647 --> 26:48.232
<i>I'm going home today because,</i>

26:48.232 --> 26:50.609
<i>it was honestly</i>
<i>my welding of my cubes</i>

26:50.609 --> 26:52.903
<i>in the beginning that</i>
<i>led to all my problems.</i>

26:52.903 --> 26:54.655
<i>But, going forward,</i>
<i>I've learned a lot,</i>

26:54.655 --> 26:56.115
<i>and I picked up a bromance.</i>

26:56.115 --> 26:58.450
<i>I got a bro down</i>
<i>in Florida now.</i>

26:58.450 --> 27:00.410
So, that's awesome.

27:00.410 --> 27:02.371
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:02.371 --> 27:04.039
- Nick, Alex, congratulations.

27:04.039 --> 27:05.916
You guys have earned a slot

27:05.916 --> 27:07.668
in this final round
of competition,

27:07.668 --> 27:09.336
which puts you one step closer

27:09.336 --> 27:11.338
to the title of
"Forged in Fire" champion

27:11.338 --> 27:14.091
and that check for $10,000.

27:14.091 --> 27:16.093
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

27:16.093 --> 27:18.095
to re-create
an iconic weapon from history.

27:18.095 --> 27:20.097
That weapon is...

27:20.097 --> 27:22.516
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:22.516 --> 27:24.101
The glaive-guisarme.

27:24.101 --> 27:25.477
- Whoo.

27:25.477 --> 27:28.146
- What? Ah.
[laughs]

27:28.146 --> 27:29.982
<i>- Commonly seen</i>
<i>on battlefields</i>

27:29.982 --> 27:31.984
<i>during the Medieval era,</i>

27:31.984 --> 27:33.735
<i>the glaive-guisarme was one</i>
<i>of the principal weapons</i>

27:33.735 --> 27:36.154
<i>for European foot soldiers</i>
<i>in combat.</i>

27:36.154 --> 27:38.657
<i>This fearsome pole arm</i>
<i>evolved from the Celtic</i>

27:38.657 --> 27:41.451
<i>and German custom of attaching</i>
<i>swords or edged weapons</i>

27:41.451 --> 27:43.787
<i>to the end of long,</i>
<i>wooden poles.</i>

27:43.787 --> 27:46.331
<i>The combination</i>
<i>of the long, convex blade</i>

27:46.331 --> 27:48.041
<i>mounted to a wooden shaft</i>

27:48.041 --> 27:50.252
<i>was ideal for combating</i>
<i>enemies on horseback</i>

27:50.252 --> 27:52.254
<i>due to its reach</i>
<i>and versatility.</i>

27:52.254 --> 27:54.464
<i>The glaive-guisarme had</i>
<i>a signature hook or spike</i>

27:54.464 --> 27:56.592
<i>on the opposite side</i>
<i>of the blade</i>

27:56.592 --> 27:59.136
<i>to catch riders</i>
<i>and move enemy pikes.</i>

27:59.136 --> 28:01.513
<i>Cheap to produce</i>
<i>and deadly against cavalry,</i>

28:01.513 --> 28:03.432
<i>the glaive-guisarme was</i>
<i>essential on the battlefield</i>

28:03.432 --> 28:05.142
<i>for hundreds of years,</i>

28:05.142 --> 28:06.894
<i>until it was phased out</i>
<i>in the 18th century.</i>

28:06.894 --> 28:08.061
[men shouting]

28:08.061 --> 28:10.063
[canon booms]

28:10.063 --> 28:12.274
It must be an effective
working version

28:12.274 --> 28:13.942
of this French pole arm.

28:13.942 --> 28:16.111
However, you're both
talented bladesmiths.

28:16.111 --> 28:18.030
Put your own spin on it,

28:18.030 --> 28:20.157
but make sure it falls within
the following parameters.

28:20.157 --> 28:22.367
The length of your
single-edged blade

28:22.367 --> 28:24.912
must be between
26 and 28 inches,

28:24.912 --> 28:26.788
with two langets,

28:26.788 --> 28:29.499
and you must have
a back spike.

28:29.499 --> 28:32.169
Bladesmiths, you will have
five days at your home forge

28:32.169 --> 28:33.754
to complete this project.

28:33.754 --> 28:35.339
At the end of five days,

28:35.339 --> 28:36.673
you will return
to present your weapons

28:36.673 --> 28:38.342
to our panel
of expert judges.

28:38.342 --> 28:40.469
And only after
they've thoroughly tested them

28:40.469 --> 28:42.846
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" Champion

28:42.846 --> 28:46.058
and hand you that check
for $10,000.

28:46.058 --> 28:47.643
Good luck, bladesmiths.
You're going to need it.

28:47.643 --> 28:48.894
See you in five days.

28:48.894 --> 28:50.437
- Man.

28:50.437 --> 28:54.024
<i>[funk music]</i>

28:54.024 --> 28:56.652
<i>- My shop is a pretty</i>
<i>traditional setup.</i>

28:56.652 --> 28:59.321
Gonna be moving metal
a lot slower.

28:59.321 --> 29:01.073
<i>I'm starting out</i>
<i>by going through</i>

29:01.073 --> 29:02.699
<i>a bunch of</i>
<i>different resources,</i>

29:02.699 --> 29:05.118
<i>comparing different designs.</i>

29:05.118 --> 29:07.204
<i>I actually have quite</i>
<i>a bit of experience</i>

29:07.204 --> 29:09.873
in Medieval re-enactment
and primitive agriculture.

29:09.873 --> 29:12.000
<i>I'm hoping</i>
<i>that'll give me a good feel</i>

29:12.000 --> 29:15.337
for what this thing
needs to move like.

29:15.337 --> 29:17.839
I'm hoping today
to get at least a big chunk

29:17.839 --> 29:20.676
of the rough forging out.

29:20.676 --> 29:22.928
Oh, I'm still not quite getting
the kind of heat I'd like.

29:22.928 --> 29:24.805
<i>I need a bigger blower,</i>

29:24.805 --> 29:27.432
and the biggest blower that
I've got is a shop vacuum

29:27.432 --> 29:30.602
This is exactly what
they always tell you not to do.

29:30.602 --> 29:31.937
So?

29:31.937 --> 29:35.482
[vacuum whirring]

29:35.482 --> 29:37.985
That's what I'm talking about.

29:37.985 --> 29:42.948
But it's not taking a whole lot
of time for me to air out.

29:42.948 --> 29:47.077
It'd be easier with a big,
burly man to strike for me.

29:47.077 --> 29:50.789
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:50.789 --> 29:53.208
<i>- I'm ready to start building,</i>
<i>and I'm pretty excited.</i>

29:53.208 --> 29:55.252
The glaive I'm building
has a lot of extra features.

29:55.252 --> 29:56.920
<i>It's got a nice,</i>
<i>big spike on the back.</i>

29:56.920 --> 30:00.716
<i>Today I'm going to focus</i>
<i>mainly on the blade.</i>

30:00.716 --> 30:03.093
What a big,
awkward piece of metal.

30:03.093 --> 30:05.429
I'm having trouble fitting some
of the parts

30:05.429 --> 30:07.180
into some of the machines
that I want to use,

30:07.180 --> 30:09.057
so I'm having to do
a lot of it by hand.

30:09.057 --> 30:11.268
<i>[rock music]</i>

30:11.268 --> 30:13.103
The steel I've chosen
to make the socket out of

30:13.103 --> 30:15.564
<i>is just a regular</i>
<i>mild steel pipe.</i>

30:15.564 --> 30:17.649
<i>I think that the softness that</i>
<i>that steel will have</i>

30:17.649 --> 30:19.776
will lend very well
to what I need it to do,

30:19.776 --> 30:22.070
which is
hold everything together.

30:22.070 --> 30:23.655
<i>Right now I'm feeling pretty</i>
<i>good about my progress.</i>

30:23.655 --> 30:25.365
<i>I got a lot done today.</i>

30:25.365 --> 30:27.367
<i>It's still a huge, awkward</i>
<i>piece of metal.</i>

30:27.367 --> 30:29.161
<i>But now that I'm starting</i>
<i>to get some shape in there,</i>

30:29.161 --> 30:31.997
<i>it's starting to look like</i>
<i>what I'm going for.</i>

30:31.997 --> 30:34.041
I'm ready to go home,
take a cold shower,

30:34.041 --> 30:36.001
and get ready to start thinking
about tomorrow morning.

30:36.001 --> 30:39.337
- I'm excited to get things
moving along.

30:39.337 --> 30:40.714
<i>I have something</i>
<i>that looks like a blade,</i>

30:40.714 --> 30:42.424
<i>so that's positive.</i>

30:42.424 --> 30:45.510
My plan is to forge out
a separate socket,

30:45.510 --> 30:50.265
and then, hopefully, forge weld
the socket onto the tang.

30:50.265 --> 30:52.392
<i>Forge welding the socket</i>
<i>onto the blade</i>

30:52.392 --> 30:53.977
<i>is making me</i>
<i>kind of nervous.</i>

30:53.977 --> 30:56.104
I don't do a whole lot
of forge welding.

30:56.104 --> 30:58.273
I'm not
getting a good heat.

30:58.273 --> 31:01.401
I understand the principles.
I've done it a few times.

31:01.401 --> 31:05.072
I just can't get the two pieces
of metal mated up in time,

31:05.072 --> 31:07.157
<i>to try to stick the weld.</i>

31:07.157 --> 31:10.869
So that obviously didn't work.
One more time.

31:10.869 --> 31:14.873
Ah...come on, you can do it.
You can do it.

31:14.873 --> 31:19.294
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

31:19.294 --> 31:21.379
For a moment,
it seems like it's on there.

31:21.379 --> 31:24.299
<i>- Start of day three.</i>
<i>I got a good night's sleep.</i>

31:24.299 --> 31:25.425
Ready to get to work.

31:25.425 --> 31:27.177
<i>At the end of today,</i>

31:27.177 --> 31:29.012
<i>I would love to have</i>
<i>the blade hardened.</i>

31:29.012 --> 31:31.014
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:31.014 --> 31:34.392
My weapon is too long
for either oven.

31:34.392 --> 31:36.311
And I want to make sure
I get a good heat treat.

31:36.311 --> 31:40.315
So, we are running
dueling ovens.

31:40.315 --> 31:42.025
Really got to get
this quench done today.

31:42.025 --> 31:46.446
It's really crucial for me
to keep this timeline.

31:46.446 --> 31:48.198
There we go.

31:48.198 --> 31:51.159
Everything seems
to be going according to plan.

31:51.159 --> 31:53.203
Just need this [bleep] fire
to go out.

31:53.203 --> 31:54.621
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:54.621 --> 31:56.164
Mother[bleep].

31:56.164 --> 31:58.083
<i>I can't get the fire</i>
<i>to go out.</i>

31:58.083 --> 32:00.109
I need to pull my blade out
so I can straighten it.

32:06.299 --> 32:08.343
Ready with
th
All right, good.

32:08.343 --> 32:10.345
As I'm examining the blade
after the quench,

32:10.345 --> 32:11.805
<i>I notice there's a little bit</i>
<i>of warp in it</i>

32:11.805 --> 32:13.723
<i>that I'm not</i>
<i>real happy with.</i>

32:13.723 --> 32:15.142
Typically, with any other blade
that I'm quenching,

32:15.142 --> 32:16.476
you do have a window of time

32:16.476 --> 32:17.727
after the quench
to straighten out

32:17.727 --> 32:19.688
<i>some minor problems.</i>

32:19.688 --> 32:21.940
Unfortunately, that window
has passed due to the fire.

32:21.940 --> 32:23.400
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:23.400 --> 32:25.443
Well, that's fun.

32:25.443 --> 32:27.279
<i>I think we may be abandoning</i>
<i>the quench for today,</i>

32:27.279 --> 32:29.322
and I might just wait
until tomorrow morning,

32:29.322 --> 32:32.033
and come at it
with some fresh peepers.

32:32.033 --> 32:33.994
<i>We need to win,</i>
<i>is what we need at this point.</i>

32:33.994 --> 32:35.495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:35.495 --> 32:36.830
- I'm a little nervous
about everything

32:36.830 --> 32:38.415
that I know I still need to do.

32:38.415 --> 32:40.000
<i>This is the real</i>
<i>time-consuming stuff,</i>

32:40.000 --> 32:41.877
<i>to get fit and finish right.</i>

32:41.877 --> 32:43.378
<i>If I can pull it</i>
<i>all together quick,</i>

32:43.378 --> 32:45.463
I should be in decent shape.

32:45.463 --> 32:49.593
Now, let that cool down, and
start working on these langets.

32:49.593 --> 32:53.013
<i>I'm not 100% sure how I'm</i>
<i>going to attach these langets,</i>

32:53.013 --> 32:56.516
so I'm just going to have to
move along at a good clip.

32:56.516 --> 32:58.935
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:58.935 --> 33:00.979
I'm going to call that good.

33:00.979 --> 33:02.731
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:02.731 --> 33:04.691
<i>I know</i>
<i>it's a critical parameter</i>

33:04.691 --> 33:06.776
<i>to make sure that</i>
<i>the head doesn't come loose,</i>

33:06.776 --> 33:08.486
but I'm getting
pretty impatient.

33:08.486 --> 33:10.113
Hope that's good enough.

33:10.113 --> 33:12.490
I would definitely do it
different and better

33:12.490 --> 33:13.992
if I were to do it again.

33:13.992 --> 33:15.869
<i>But, you know,</i>
<i>for here and now,</i>

33:15.869 --> 33:18.663
<i>I'm pretty happy with it.</i>

33:18.663 --> 33:20.540
Well, it prunes.

33:21.875 --> 33:23.043
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:23.043 --> 33:25.212
<i>- Yeah, starting day five.</i>

33:25.212 --> 33:27.380
<i>It's assembly day.</i>

33:27.380 --> 33:29.174
<i>So, I'm feeling good about</i>
<i>everything I've done this far.</i>

33:29.174 --> 33:30.717
<i>I'm just ready to get</i>
<i>this thing put together</i>

33:30.717 --> 33:32.636
and get it out of here.

33:32.636 --> 33:34.596
<i>Preparing the wood to be</i>
<i>inserted into the socket,</i>

33:34.596 --> 33:36.181
<i>I've left it pretty snug,</i>

33:36.181 --> 33:37.807
<i>so it's going to be</i>
<i>a hammer fit.</i>

33:37.807 --> 33:40.435
Ultimately, if the size
is a little bit off,

33:40.435 --> 33:42.479
<i>sometimes you can have</i>
<i>hang-ups and have problems.</i>

33:42.479 --> 33:44.189
Oh, I missed.

33:44.189 --> 33:46.816
Oh, I hit myself real hard
in the tummy.

33:46.816 --> 33:47.984
Oh, it's going to be on TV.

33:47.984 --> 33:49.569
Oh, it hurts so bad.

33:49.569 --> 33:50.820
How'd you get hurt
on "Forged in Fire"?

33:50.820 --> 33:52.239
Oh, I cut a finger off.

33:52.239 --> 33:54.449
Oh, I lost a toe
dropping a knife on it.

33:54.449 --> 33:55.533
What'd you do, Alex?

33:55.533 --> 33:57.244
Oh, I missed.

33:57.244 --> 33:58.954
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:58.954 --> 34:00.956
<i>It's the end of day five.</i>

34:00.956 --> 34:04.084
I've completed my weapon,
and I feel great about it.

34:04.084 --> 34:07.295
<i>I put my best forward</i>
<i>and I left it all out there.</i>

34:07.295 --> 34:08.797
I'm excited to see
what it does,

34:08.797 --> 34:10.423
<i>and I think it'll do well.</i>

34:10.423 --> 34:14.928
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:14.928 --> 34:17.264
- Nick, Alex, welcome back
to The Forge.

34:17.264 --> 34:19.307
You've had five days
at your home forges

34:19.307 --> 34:21.184
to work on
your glaive-guisarmes.

34:21.184 --> 34:22.185
Nick, how did it go?

34:22.185 --> 34:24.187
- It was pretty rough.

34:24.187 --> 34:27.607
<i>The cutting edge is from</i>
<i>a large truck leaf spring.</i>

34:27.607 --> 34:30.193
Did a lot of new things,
but I got it done in the end.

34:30.193 --> 34:32.112
- Alex, how'd it go for you?

34:32.112 --> 34:33.655
- It was a lot of fun,
a lot of work.

34:33.655 --> 34:36.491
<i>I used 52-100 steel,</i>

34:36.491 --> 34:39.119
<i>and then did the leather wrap</i>
<i>for some style points.</i>

34:39.119 --> 34:40.537
I think I did
the best thing I could.

34:40.537 --> 34:41.621
- All right, gentlemen.

34:41.621 --> 34:42.956
Your weapons will now be put

34:42.956 --> 34:44.291
through a series
of three tests.

34:44.291 --> 34:46.793
Up first: kill test.
Doug?

34:46.793 --> 34:48.837
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:48.837 --> 34:51.131
- To see what kind of lethal
damage your weapon will do,

34:51.131 --> 34:53.550
I'll take your glaive-guisarme,
and deliver thrusts and slashes

34:53.550 --> 34:55.093
on this deer carcass.

34:55.093 --> 34:56.553
Nick, you're up first.
Are you ready?

34:56.553 --> 34:59.097
- Guess so.
- Let's do this.

34:59.097 --> 35:00.849
- Yeah,
I'm feeling pretty good.

35:00.849 --> 35:02.434
<i>I'm just excited to see</i>
<i>what's going to happen.</i>

35:02.434 --> 35:03.977
<i>I'm hoping this is</i>
<i>the only big dead animal</i>

35:03.977 --> 35:06.396
I have to deal with today.

35:06.396 --> 35:08.106
- To be my arm today,

35:08.106 --> 35:10.734
bladesmiths, please
welcome back RJ Marcaida.

35:10.734 --> 35:13.528
Today,
he will wield your weapon.

35:16.072 --> 35:19.075
<i>[rock music]</i>

35:19.075 --> 35:25.999
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:27.626 --> 35:32.255
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:32.255 --> 35:35.175
- First up,
right here on your edge,

35:35.175 --> 35:37.677
it picked up a chip.

35:37.677 --> 35:39.262
On another side of this,

35:39.262 --> 35:41.306
you can feel where
the edge also rolled.

35:41.306 --> 35:43.266
But this weapon is sharp.

35:43.266 --> 35:45.894
On initial thrusts,
it's got a geometry right there

35:45.894 --> 35:47.812
to penetrate it
deep into the carcass.

35:47.812 --> 35:50.398
Your edge right here,
on slashing,

35:50.398 --> 35:53.652
it lacerated easily on the side
of this deer carcass.

35:53.652 --> 35:56.988
On the third cut, the weight of
this weapon is so balanced,

35:56.988 --> 35:59.324
that it's easy to lacerate
all the way through.

35:59.324 --> 36:01.534
Your weapon will kill.

36:01.534 --> 36:03.370
- Thank you.

36:03.370 --> 36:05.330
- All right, Alex.
Your turn.

36:05.330 --> 36:07.707
<i>- His seems to do really well.</i>
<i>It stabs right through.</i>

36:07.707 --> 36:09.292
It slashes real nicely.

36:09.292 --> 36:11.628
<i>So, I'm excited</i>
<i>to see what mine does.</i>

36:11.628 --> 36:13.588
I'm, like, a little bit,
like, throwy-uppy,

36:13.588 --> 36:15.423
like, to right there.

36:18.218 --> 36:25.183
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:26.851 --> 36:29.854
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:29.854 --> 36:32.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:32.982 --> 36:34.609
- All right, Alex.

36:34.609 --> 36:36.986
Your tip is sharp enough

36:36.986 --> 36:38.905
to lacerate
all the way through.

36:38.905 --> 36:41.116
On the slash of this edge,

36:41.116 --> 36:46.037
it lacerated easily on the side
rib of this particular carcass.

36:46.037 --> 36:50.625
On the wide swing, it did
break half of the spine off.

36:50.625 --> 36:53.336
It is, as you can see,
a little bit on the wider side.

36:53.336 --> 36:54.921
With a heavy weapon like this,

36:54.921 --> 36:57.090
a wide handle can make it
hard to control.

36:57.090 --> 36:59.634
- Yeah.
- But the most important thing,

36:59.634 --> 37:00.760
it will kill.

37:00.760 --> 37:01.928
- Thank you.

37:01.928 --> 37:03.304
- All right, gentlemen,

37:03.304 --> 37:04.556
it's time
for the strength test.

37:04.556 --> 37:06.224
The pike chop.

37:06.224 --> 37:07.851
[pikes rattle]

37:07.851 --> 37:11.146
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

37:11.146 --> 37:13.857
- That was intense.
I wasn't ready for that.

37:13.857 --> 37:15.442
- Often in pike warfare,

37:15.442 --> 37:16.985
the glaives
or weapons like them

37:16.985 --> 37:18.820
are used as
a secondary line of defense,

37:18.820 --> 37:20.155
to push the pike up
out of the way

37:20.155 --> 37:22.031
and/or to chop
at the pike shaft.

37:22.031 --> 37:24.409
So, to test the strength and
durability of your weapons,

37:24.409 --> 37:26.119
including the hook on the back,

37:26.119 --> 37:28.288
I'll be pushing
these pikes up into position,

37:28.288 --> 37:29.998
then chopping at them
with the blade.

37:29.998 --> 37:31.833
All right, Nick.
You're up first, you ready?

37:31.833 --> 37:33.960
- Yes, sir.

37:33.960 --> 37:37.464
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:37.464 --> 37:39.591
[pikes clatter]

37:39.591 --> 37:46.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:49.934 --> 37:51.895
- [whispers]
I'd say that's pretty good.

37:51.895 --> 37:53.229
- All right, so, Nick,

37:53.229 --> 37:54.355
it doesn't look like
your weapon took

37:54.355 --> 37:55.940
any more damage to the edge.

37:55.940 --> 37:59.027
The weight of your blade
is very nicely balanced.

37:59.027 --> 38:00.737
A good design.
Definitely a strong blade.

38:00.737 --> 38:01.738
Nicely done.

38:01.738 --> 38:03.198
- Thank you.

38:03.198 --> 38:05.408
- Alex, are you ready?
- Yes, sir.

38:05.408 --> 38:07.702
I'm in and out of,
"I think I got this,"

38:07.702 --> 38:10.079
to, "I have no idea
what's gonna happen."

38:10.079 --> 38:11.748
<i>So, I still feel</i>
<i>I got a good shot.</i>

38:11.748 --> 38:13.333
<i>I think I'm still</i>
<i>in the running.</i>

38:13.333 --> 38:14.503
- [whispers]
Kick ass.

38:19.214 --> 38:21.132
- Don't break it.
Be nice.

38:21.132 --> 38:28.014
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:32.227 --> 38:35.980
That was brutal, dude.
[laughs]

38:35.980 --> 38:38.775
- First off, your blade
did take some damage here.

38:38.775 --> 38:42.237
There are very small
chips and rolls.

38:42.237 --> 38:44.531
Your flanges here
are just wide enough

38:44.531 --> 38:46.783
that when I pushed forward,
I managed to grab two rows

38:46.783 --> 38:49.202
of pikes and push them back
at the same time.

38:49.202 --> 38:50.495
Balance is nice on it.

38:50.495 --> 38:52.163
The shaft is pretty wide.

38:52.163 --> 38:53.623
It's not too big,

38:53.623 --> 38:55.792
but it's right
on the outside edge

38:55.792 --> 38:58.044
of what's comfortable
for my hand.

38:58.044 --> 38:59.796
But everything held up.
Everything's solid.

38:59.796 --> 39:01.881
- Thank you.

39:01.881 --> 39:04.384
<i>- Because Alex's blade picked</i>
<i>a couple of chips up,</i>

39:04.384 --> 39:06.052
we're really even closer to
even at this point.

39:06.052 --> 39:07.637
- All right, gentlemen.

39:07.637 --> 39:09.013
Now it's time
for the sharpness test.

39:09.013 --> 39:10.390
To test the sharpness
of your blade,

39:10.390 --> 39:11.432
I'll be cutting
these ropes.

39:11.432 --> 39:12.892
Now, that releases the bag,

39:12.892 --> 39:13.977
and then I'll be
cutting the bag.

39:13.977 --> 39:15.937
Now, unlike the strength test,

39:15.937 --> 39:18.648
this is all about what your
weapons do to these targets.

39:18.648 --> 39:20.400
Nick, you're up first.
Are you ready?

39:20.400 --> 39:22.443
- Good.

39:22.443 --> 39:24.988
<i>This is obviously the</i>
<i>final test that's coming up.</i>

39:24.988 --> 39:28.074
It's going to be
the deciding factor--who wins.

39:28.074 --> 39:29.450
<i>I think we're still running</i>
<i>neck and neck,</i>

39:29.450 --> 39:32.245
so it's fun to have
a tight race.

39:32.245 --> 39:39.168
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:42.380 --> 39:45.508
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:45.508 --> 39:47.218
[whispers]
That's pretty cool.

39:47.218 --> 39:49.012
- Yeah.
- Well, Nick,

39:49.012 --> 39:50.847
it cut through the bags
really cleanly,

39:50.847 --> 39:53.182
and what I really like
is the balance of this weapon.

39:53.182 --> 39:55.018
It's very easy to maneuver.

39:55.018 --> 39:56.644
I didn't have
to fight the weapon.

39:56.644 --> 39:58.271
Nicely done.
- Thank you.

39:58.271 --> 39:59.814
- All right, Alex, you're up.
Are you ready?

39:59.814 --> 40:01.649
- Yes, sir.

40:01.649 --> 40:03.568
I feel like we are pretty
neck and neck this far.

40:03.568 --> 40:05.528
<i>If mine doesn't do well,</i>

40:05.528 --> 40:06.905
<i>I think it's pretty clear</i>
<i>what's going to happen.</i>

40:06.905 --> 40:08.573
And if it does,
I'm just at a loss.

40:08.573 --> 40:10.199
I have no idea.

40:10.199 --> 40:16.956
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:21.628 --> 40:25.006
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:25.006 --> 40:28.551
- All right.
Your blade is wicked sharp.

40:28.551 --> 40:29.594
- Thank you.
- This passed

40:29.594 --> 40:30.720
right through the rope.

40:30.720 --> 40:32.221
Very little resistance at all.

40:32.221 --> 40:34.223
And it cut the bags
beautifully.

40:34.223 --> 40:36.935
The balance of your blade is
a little bit more to the tip.

40:36.935 --> 40:38.436
- Mm-hmm.
- So, the one thing

40:38.436 --> 40:40.229
about this blade,
when I cut with it,

40:40.229 --> 40:42.065
it's slowing it down
after the cut.

40:42.065 --> 40:45.276
But it's a beautiful cutter.
You did a great job.

40:45.276 --> 40:46.235
- Thank you.
- Nicely done.

40:46.235 --> 40:48.321
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:48.321 --> 40:50.323
- Nick, Alex, you've both done
an incredible amount of work

40:50.323 --> 40:52.325
on your finale weapons.

40:52.325 --> 40:54.786
However, there can only be one
"Forged in Fire" champion.

40:54.786 --> 40:56.663
And that champion is...

40:56.663 --> 40:59.582
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:59.582 --> 41:01.167
Nick.

41:01.167 --> 41:02.752
Congratulations.

41:02.752 --> 41:05.672
You are our next
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:05.672 --> 41:08.257
Alex, unfortunately, your
weapon didn't make the cut.

41:08.257 --> 41:10.385
David Baker is
going to tell you why.

41:10.385 --> 41:12.637
- Alex, you both brought us
beautiful weapons.

41:12.637 --> 41:14.013
Both your weapons took damage.

41:14.013 --> 41:15.515
It really came down to

41:15.515 --> 41:17.558
that large handle
and that forward weight.

41:17.558 --> 41:19.852
It's that fine a point
that is sending you home.

41:19.852 --> 41:22.438
- Alex,
please surrender your blade.

41:22.438 --> 41:24.440
<i>- So, the final judgment,</i>

41:24.440 --> 41:26.526
<i>I am not the</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

41:26.526 --> 41:28.403
There's definitely a long road
to get all the way here,

41:28.403 --> 41:30.363
and it is disappointing,
but Nick won.

41:30.363 --> 41:32.115
<i>He absolutely killed it.</i>

41:32.115 --> 41:34.075
<i>He made a great weapon.</i>
<i>I'm super happy for him.</i>

41:34.075 --> 41:35.994
<i>It was a tight race, so--</i>

41:35.994 --> 41:38.162
It's been a fun experience,
but it's back to work now.

41:38.162 --> 41:39.664
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:39.664 --> 41:41.290
- Nick, congratulations.

41:41.290 --> 41:43.209
You are our new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:43.209 --> 41:45.044
and that's a title that comes
with a check for ten grand.

41:45.044 --> 41:46.129
Good job.

41:46.129 --> 41:47.130
[applause]

41:47.130 --> 41:48.965
- Thank you.

41:48.965 --> 41:50.967
- Nick, please present
your weapon to the judges.

41:50.967 --> 41:52.927
<i>- I'm "Forged in Fire"</i>
<i>champion.</i>

41:52.927 --> 41:54.762
<i>That's so weird.</i>
<i>But awesome.</i>

41:54.762 --> 41:56.472
What can I say?
I made the right choices

41:56.472 --> 41:58.766
with the handle,
slimming it down a little bit.

41:58.766 --> 42:00.309
<i>I got to make</i>
<i>some really cool stuff,</i>

42:00.309 --> 42:01.853
meet some
really cool people,

42:01.853 --> 42:03.438
<i>and being champion,</i>

42:03.438 --> 42:05.356
<i>that's just</i>
<i>a really cool bonus.</i>

42:05.356 --> 42:09.444
<i>♪ ♪</i>
